From the <i>Weekly Irish Times</i> of Saturday, 5 April 1913...

John O'Neill's cycle and engineering works was established in 1894. He started to build bikes in a small premises on South King Street in Dublin. 99% of bikes at that stage were imported. O'Neill started by importing the parts and assembling on South King Street. Quality was so good that he took the adjoining shop in 1906 &quot;and the present fine premises in South King street built, the works in connection with which were installed with a complete plant for the manufacture of cycle parts.&quot;

At this stage, John O'Neill went into manufacturing <b>Lucania</b> bicycles, which apparently had a great reputation for quality. Orders went through the roof. &quot;In 1911, it may here be stated, Mr. O'Neill secured the contract in open competition with the leading English manufacturers for 400 machines for the G.P.O. delivery service, and last year [1912] he received an order for a further 400 cycles from the Postmaster-General.&quot;

In 1907, O'Neill took over Irish Plating and Enamelling on Great Brunswick (now Pearse) Street. In 1912, O'Neill opened &quot;the extensive factory in Pleasants street, the formal opening being performed by His Excellency the Lord Lieutenant, who, in the course of an interesting address, warmly congratulated Mr. O'Neill on his energy and enterprise, and on the steadily growing prosperity of the industry...&quot;

I've had a look at the photo of the new Pleasants Street factory in the <i>Weekly Irish Times</i>. The quality is abysmal, but I'd be fairly happy that this photo wasn't taken there, so presumably this was at the South King Street premises... Apart from size, etc., Pleasants Street was fully electrified, and I think we have gas lighting in this photo?
